Sir '''Roy Malcolm Anderson''' [[Royal Society|FRS]] (born 12 April 1947) is a leading [[United Kingdom|British]] expert on [[epidemiology]]. He has mathematically modelled the spread of diseases such as new variant [[Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease]] and [[AIDS]]. He also currently chairs the science advisory board of [[World Health Organization|WHO]]'s Neglected Tropical Diseases programme, is a member of the Bill and Melinda Gates [[Grand Challenges In Global Health]] advisory board, and chairs the Schistosomiasis Control Initiative (SCI) advisory board funded by the Gates Foundation. He is a non-executive director of [[GlaxoSmithKline]].

==Biography==
===Education and early life===
Anderson was born the son of James Anderson and Betty Watson-Weatherborn.<ref name="ww" /> He attended Duncombe School, Bengeo and [[Richard Hale School]]. He gained a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] degree in [[zoology]] at [[Imperial College]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree in [[parasitology]] in 1971 with thesis titled ''A quantitative ecological study of the helminth parasites of the bream [[Abramis brama]] (L)''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Population Dynamics of the Cestode Caryophyllaeus laticeps (Pallas, 1781) in the Bream (Abramis brama L.)|first=Roy M.|last=Anderson|authorlink=Roy M. Anderson|journal=Journal of Animal Ecology|volume=43|number=2|year=1974|pages=305–321|publisher=British Ecological Society|doi=10.2307/3367|issue=2|jstor=3367}}</ref> Most of Anderson's early career was at Imperial College, becoming Professor of [[Parasite Ecology]] in 1982. He was head of the Department of Biology from 1984 to 1993.<ref name="ww" /> At Imperial College, he served as Director of the Wellcome Centre for Parasite Infections from 1989 to 1993.

===Career===
In 1993 Anderson moved to the [[University of Oxford]] where he was head of the Zoology department and held the [[Linacre Chair of Zoology]] until 2000. During this time he served as Director, [[Wellcome Centre for the Epidemiology of Infectious Disease]]. 

Anderson is the author of over 450 scientific articles and has sat on numerous government and international agency committees advising on public health and disease control including the World Health Organisation and UNAIDS. From 1991–2000, he was a Governor of the [[Wellcome Trust]].

'''Foot and mouth'''<br>
Anderson was one of the most prominent scientists who advised the UK Government on the handling of the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth crisis|Foot and Mouth control policy in 2001]].

'''Chief Scientific Advisor'''<br>
He was [[MoD Chief Scientific Adviser|Chief Scientific Advisor]] to the UK [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] from October 2004 to September 2007. After that, he returned to his Chair in Infectious Disease Epidemiology at the [[Department of Infectious Disease Epidemiology]] at [[Imperial College London]].<ref>[http://www.imperial.ac.uk/rector/biography/ Prof. Anderson's Biography at Imperial College], as of 2 July 2008.</ref>

'''Rector of Imperial College'''<br>
Anderson succeeded [[Richard Sykes (biochemist)|Richard Sykes]] as the 14th [[Rector of Imperial College]] on 1 July 2008. In this role he expressed a desire to raise tuition fees<ref>{{cite web | title = Rector Endorses Tuition Fee Rise | url = http://live.cgcu.net/news/1936 | last = Patterson | first = Kirsty | last2 = Shubber | first2 = Kadhim | publisher = Imperial College Live! | date = 2009-03-12 | accessdate = 2009-06-02 }}</ref> and [[private university|privatise]] top UK universities within 10–20 years.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://live.cgcu.net/news/1971?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_content=1971 | title = Rector on Privatisation of Higher Education | publisher = Imperial College Live! | last = Patterson | first = Kirsty | date = 2009-06-01 | accessdate = 2009-06-02 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/5422883/Top-universities-should-sever-ties-with-Government.html | title = Top universities 'should sever ties with Government' | newspaper = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | last = Paton | first = Graeme | date = 2009-06-01 | accessdate = 2009-06-02 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/422fed86-4ef5-11de-8c10-00144feabdc0.html | title = Imperial seeks Ivy League status over fees | last = Turner | first = David | newspaper = [[Financial Times]] | date = 2009-06-01 | accessdate = 2009-06-02 }}</ref> He tendered his resignation in November 2009 stating "I have decided to step down as rector as I want to return to my primary concern, which is my deep and abiding research interest into global health."<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5e41cee6-d2b6-11de-af63-00144feabdc0.html | title = Imperial College head to resign | last = Turner | first = David | newspaper = [[Financial Times]] | date = 2009-11-16 | accessdate = 2009-11-16 }}</ref>

== Honours ==
Anderson was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society]] in 1986, and an Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal Statistical Society]] in 2004. He was knighted in the 2006 Queen's Birthday Honours list.

== Personal life ==
In 1975, he married Mary Joan Mitchell, whom he later divorced in 1989. In 1990, he married Claire Baron. He enjoys [[hill walking]], [[croquet]], [[natural history]] and [[photography]].<ref name="ww" />

